    <div class="container" style="max-width: 900px;">
      <h2 id="problem-heading" class="section-title">The Storage Industry's Hidden Fee Problem</h2>

      <div style="font-family: 'Open Sans', sans-serif; font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text-dark); line-height: 1.8;">
        <p style="margin-bottom: 18px;">
          Storage pricing has a transparency problem. National chains and many independent facilities advertise low monthly rates — then add charges at signing that inflate the actual cost by 20–40%. By the time you've loaded a truck and driven to the facility, you're committed. The fees get paid because the alternative is loading everything back up and driving somewhere else.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 18px;">
          The most common hidden charges include admin or "setup" fees ($25–$50 at signing), mandatory lock purchases ($10–$20), required protection plans or insurance ($10–$20/month added to every bill), and rate increases that kick in after the promotional period ends — typically 3–6 months. A unit advertised at "$99/month" can actually cost $130–$150/month once add-ons are included.
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
          James Richards built Fort Knox Self Storage to be the straightforward alternative. The price advertised is the price charged. Nothing added at signing. Nothing added later. That's not a marketing gimmick — it's how a locally-owned business operates when the owner answers his own phone and looks customers in the eye in the Vernal Walmart.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


